<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759"><gtr:id>AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Hills Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Cambridge</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>CB2 2QH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759"><gtr:id>AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Hills Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Cambridge</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>CB2 2QH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/EF9698BC-8A06-4CC0-915B-C106F9C43D72"><gtr:id>EF9698BC-8A06-4CC0-915B-C106F9C43D72</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>J</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Kilmartin</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U105184282"><gtr:id>CDEEAE5A-68EA-458A-96E7-711EE2A3D45C</gtr:id><gtr:title>Spindle Pole Body duplication</gtr:title><gtr:status>Active</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U105184282</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>When cells divide the chromosomes are divided equally between the two cells by an organelle called the mitotic spindle. The spindle has two poles which pull the two sets of chromosomes into either cell. The poles of the spindle are formed by an organelle called the centrosome in most cells and the spindle pole body (SPB) in the simple yeast cell. Prior to mitosis all of these cells have only one copy of the centrosome or SPB and can only form one pole of the spindle. Just before mitosis the centrosome and SPB duplicate themselves to produce a single exact copy, and thus can then form the two poles of the spindle, necessary to segregate the chromosomes accurately to each cell. I have proposed a mechanism to explain this duplication whereby a template attached to the mother centriole or SPB initiates the assembly of the new centriole or SPB. I have isolated a novel conserved protein and am testing whether this protein is part of the template structure in both SPBs and centrioles.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>We have proposed a molecular model for SPB duplication based on the identification of core SPB components and their localization by immuno-electron microscopy during SPB duplication. A central feature of the model is the half-bridge, a specialized membranous structure attached to one side of the SPB, and the ability of the half-bridge to bind core SPB components at either end. I have identified a new half-bridge component, Sfi1p, which binds multiple copies of the yeast centrin, Cdc31p, through a continuous set of novel repeats. 
I am investigating the role of Sfi1p in SPB duplication by looking at its interactions with other SPB components and its role in the morphology of the half-bridge. 
I am also characterizing a potential human homologue of Sfi1p, hSfi1 which localizes close to centrioles, and whether it has a role in centriole duplication.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>1977-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1207706</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>36A6F15F-B5A5-48C0-B591-278968B4C651</gtr:id><gtr:title>Structural role of Sfi1p-centrin filaments in budding yeast spindle pole body duplication.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of cell biology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b8a46f3752fd4026773cf1b531707cbf"><gtr:id>b8a46f3752fd4026773cf1b531707cbf</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Li S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2006-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0021-9525</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>74EA8F290A2</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>49C3F382-7D9B-43B6-9502-CA7FBA85C475</gtr:id><gtr:title>Lessons from yeast: the spindle pole body and the centrosome.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Philosophical transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Biological sciences</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/f7cc694c70ad2aa66a2fa0732756ca3b"><gtr:id>f7cc694c70ad2aa66a2fa0732756ca3b</gtr:id><gtr:oth